      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, thanks for telling me about this — two weeks of sharp knee pain is something worth taking seriously, and I'm glad you're not just pushing through it quietly.\n\nI have to be straight with you here: **diagnosing what's causing your knee pain is genuinely outside my lane as a running coach.** Sharp pain that's persisted for two weeks, especially on stairs, needs a proper look from a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor — someone who can actually assess what's going on in that joint. They're the right person to answer your question about ibuprofen too, since that's a medical decision that depends on what's actually happening in there.\n\nWhat I *can* tell you is this: **running through sharp, persistent pain — even shortened runs — carries real risk of turning a manageable issue into a longer setback.** I'd hate to see you lose months of training over something that a professional might be able to sort out in a week or two with the right guidance.\n\n---\n\n**Here's what I'd suggest as a clear next step:**\n\nGet in to see a physio or sports medicine doctor as soon as you can — ideally this week. When you go, mention the onset (after your long run), the location (left knee), the duration (two weeks), and the stair symptom specifically. Those details will help them a lot.\n\n**Once you have clearance and a clearer picture, I'm absolutely here to adjust your plan around it.** We have time before your July half marathon — this doesn't have to derail things. Your training history shows real consistency and you've built a solid base. That doesn't disappear.\n\n---\n\nOne thing I'm curious about while you're waiting: how are you feeling about the race goal right now — are you more worried about the knee itself, or about losing fitness during any time off?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01Any1Cad7YC8iUti8yuJpWe"
    }
